      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moderate But Mediocre</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gabriella Dahlstrom letter, commenting on May 17 article, says the moderately priced restaurants in New York are no bargain, given their mediocre food</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I found your article on the rising prices in New York's high-end restaurants very interesting and relevant. I go out for dinner several times a week in more modest establishments and am often shocked at the high prices and not so much bad, but mediocre, food and service.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I found your article on the rising prices in New York's high-end restaurants very interesting and relevant. I go out for dinner several times a week in more modest establishments and am often shocked at the high prices and not so much bad, but mediocre, food and service.</p>
        <p>I have the impression that restaurants in affluent areas like the Upper West Side are, as you said, ''seeing what they can get away with.'' As a consequence, I have decided to try to limit these mediocre $35-to-$40 dinners in favor of more rare but better $50-to-$60 dinners.</p>
        <p>GABRIELLA DAHLSTROM  New York</p>
      </block>
